webpackJsonp([0xe47a1b9eccdd],{392:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{site:{siteMetadata:{title:"Dixeed Docs",subtitle:"A blog containing various documentations, tutorials and introductions created by Dixeed",copyright:"Dixeed © All rights reserved.",author:{name:"Dixeed",twitter:"dixeed"},disqusShortname:"",url:"https://dixeed.github.io/"}},markdownRemark:{id:"/home/giaat/workspace/dixeed/github-page/src/pages/articles/2018-19-03---Database-Optimisation/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<h1>Database optimization</h1>\n<h2>PostgreSQL</h2>\n<h3>Indexes</h3>\n<p>One of the quickest and fastest way of increasing your database performance is to index your data. Several type of data should be indexed:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Primary Key: should be done automatically by the database engine.</li>\n<li>Foreign Key: it is not done by the database engine automatically so it is your responsability (or your ORM’s).</li>\n<li>Field in <code class="language-text">where</code> clause: definitely not done automatically but increases performances.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>JSONB</h4>\n<p><code class="language-text">JSONB</code> type should be index using a <code class="language-text">gin()</code> index.</p>\n<h4>Side notes</h4>\n<p>PostgreSQL does not handle composite indexes, it only indexes the first element so make sure you create indexes with only one element.</p>\n<p>30% to 40% of your database data should be indexed.</p>',fields:{tagSlugs:["/tags/postgre-sql/","/tags/database/"]},frontmatter:{title:"Database optimization",tags:["PostgreSQL","Database"],date:"2018-03-19T20:40:32.169Z",description:"Tips for database optimization"}}},pathContext:{slug:"/posts/database-optimization/"}}}});
